<HEADLINE> Kuwait GDP Rises to 30 Billion Dollars in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September (Xinhua) -- The Kuwaiti Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) surged to 30.6 billion U.S. dollars in 1996 from
26.2 billion dollars in 1995, Governor of Kuwait Central Bank
Salem Abdelaziz Al-Sabah said today.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sabah said the trade balance surplus and the current
account surplus climbed by 25.7 percent and 44.3 percent
respectively last year to hit 6.78 billion dollars and 6.5
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the actual deficit has decreased to its lowest
level during the 1995/96 fiscal year (July 1 to June 30) of 2.16
billion dollars, accounting for 7.1 percent of the GDP before
deducting allocations of oil revenues for the Future Generations
Reserves, the bank governor said.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait annually allocate, by law, 10 percent of its total
state revenues in the budget to the reserves fund which fell to
around 30 billion dollars from 100 billion dollars after
paying for the huge costs of the Gulf War. So far unofficial
sources said the fund has increased to more than 40 billion
dollars although no official figures are available.
</P>
<P>
Earnings of Kuwaiti foreign investments, mainly from this
fund, in 1996/97 exceeded actual oil revenue of over 9.9 billion
dollars in 1995/96 fiscal year, according to figures of Kuwait
Investment Authority.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the 1997 economic performance, Al-Sabah said that
1997 promises more of the same as the trade balance surplus grew
during the first half of the year to 3.18 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said that a surplus in the state budget in the 1996/97
fiscal year seemed very likely to be realized.
</P>
<P>
He said the improving world oil prices and the healthy
trading at money markets played a major role in reviving the
Kuwaiti economy.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's 1997/98 budget forecasts an oil revenues of 8.45
billion dollars which is expected to exceed because of rise in
the world oil prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
