<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti, Bahraini Stock Markets Sign Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti and Bahraini stock
markets today signed an agreement aimed at promoting cooperation
in the fields of issuance and dealings in stocks in the two Gulf
countries, according to a joint statement carried by Kuwait News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the agreement which was signed in
Manama stipulates that both markets would make available to
investors financial statements of registered companies and ensure
enhancing cooperation in dealing and issuance of registered
stocks to encourage investment.
</P>
<P>
It also provides for regulations easing conditions and
measures for dealings in stocks registered in both markets and
organizing dealings and clearance to guarantee the rights of
each party.
</P>
<P>
Joint rules to settle deals and secure the rights of
investors and their agents are also established in the
agreement, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said executive steps for the agreement would
be released within the next few days after the signing of
bilateral agreements between brokers in the two markets and
another between clearance offices in both markets.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is the second of its kind among stock
markets of the Gulf Cooperation Council's (GCC) states. GCC
groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Oman,
Qatar and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Oman and Bahrain have already linked their floors and a
number of companies from the two countries have been listed
in both exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Exchange officials believe that Kuwait and Bahrain joining
together of their markets would encourage cross-listing of
companies and the flow of capital between the two countries,
thus boosting the economic cooperation among them.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait stock exchange has been performing well since last
year and so far more than 70 companies have been listed on
the market.
</P>
<P>
On January 6, the Stock Exchange Market of Kuwait, Egypt
and Lebanon were linked together via a computer network
displaying daily deals in each country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
