<HEADLINE> Asian, European Economic Ministers Meet in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHIBA, Japan, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Economic ministers from
25 Asian and European countries began a two-day meeting today here
to study ways of accelerating cooperation in trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
Ten Asian countries - China, Japan, South Korea and seven
countries from the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
- and the 15 European Union (EU) members took part in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
During today's special session, Asian ministers introduced
their countries' economic situation and discussed the Southeast
Asian financial turmoil sparked by a Thai currency crisis, and
expressed optimism about a recovery of the region's dynamic
economy.
</P>
<P>
All 25 countries of the Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM) will start
full discussion Sunday to review the comprehensive Asian-European
economic relations, business exchanges, trade and investment,
infrastructure construction and sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is to adopt an Investment Promotion Action Plan to
promote exchange of investment-related data. It will also endorse
plans to facilitate trade and set up an investment expert group to
increase contacts between government officials.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also touch on the countries' relations with
the World Trade Organization, including China's bid for entry.
</P>
<P>
ASEM was created at an Asian-European summit in Bangkok in
March, 1996, to enhance ties between the two regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
