<HEADLINE> US, Russia Agree to Put Off Deadline on START II </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Russia
have signed a package of arms control agreements, pushing back by
five years the implementation of one of the major nuclear
disarmament treaties between the two powers in the cold war era,
U.S. and Russian officials confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
But the new package could clear the way for further cuts in
nuclear weapons of the United States and Russia, disarmament
experts said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright signed the accords
Friday at a New York hotel with Russian Foreign Minister Yevgev
Primakov, who is here to attending the 52nd session of the U.N.
General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would give Russia until the end of 2007 to
dismantle launching systems as required by the second arms
reductions treaty, or START II. However, the systems, including
missile silos, bombers and submarines, must still be disabled by
2003.
</P>
<P>
The accords were signed as the ratification of START II has
stalled in Russia. They were designed to break the logjam in the
process.
</P>
<P>
Some military and political leaders in Moscow have repeatedly
complained that START II put Russi at a strategic disadvantage
since it requires the elimination of all land-based
multiple-warhead missiles, the core of Russia's arsenal, while
allowing the United States to keep its multiple warhead missiles
on submarines.
</P>
<P>
The package put into writing the pledges made by U.S. President
Bill Clinton and Russian President Boris Yeltsin during their
meeting in Helsinki last March.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Russian leaders agreed to take steps toward
winning approval of the START II and pledged to try to cut the
number of long-range nuclear warheads by another third in a START
III.
</P>
<P>
Primakov hailed the package as "a new joint success, a radical
success in arms control" which "will determine the course of arms
control for many years to come."
</P>
<P>
He was echoed by Albright who said that the package "marks a
turning point in our approach to nuclear weapons."
</P>
<P>
"We have been very successful in mastering the challenges left
in the wake of the cold war. Now we will turn to arms control for
a new century, beyond eliminating mistrust to eliminating actual
nuclear weapons," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
