<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, September 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- China's Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
Minister Wu Yi said today that Asia and Europe have huge
potentials in the expansion of cooperation as the two regions have
great complementarity in economy.
</P>
<P>
Wu made the remarks while addressing a two-day economic session
of the Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM), which opened today in the city
of Chiba, near Tokyo. (Japan-ASEM-China)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Hundreds of Palestinian demonstrators Saturday
clashed with Israel Defense Forces (IDF) guarding the Far Deron
Jewish settlement in Gaza Strip, in which two Palestinians were
wounded.
</P>
<P>
The IDF fired rubber bullets at the Palestinians as they
approached the area for protest against Jewish settlement,
Palestine News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Today's demonstration was coincided with the one year
anniversary of the opening of the archaeological tunnel running
alongside the Al-Aqsa Mosque in Jerusalem, for which the
Palestinians and Israelis fought a battle which killed nearly 80
people. (Isreal-Palestinians-Clash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on Saturday held
talks with Chief of the South African National Defense Force
George Meiring on military cooperation between the two countries
in northern Egyptian port city of Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East News Agency reported that the meeting was
attended by chief-of-staff of the Egyptian Armed Forces Magdi
Hatata. But the report did not disclose details on the talks.
(Egypt-S. Africa)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Visiting president of Belarus Alexandr Lukashenko
said Saturday that the task of his current visit to India was to
reestablish bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that during his visit here, his country and India are
expected to sign five memoranda of understandings in various
fields of cooperation. (India-Belarus-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- The exiled executive organ of the outlawed Islamic
Salvation Front (FIS) of Algeria Saturday called for a truce
between the Algerian government and Islamic groups and urged the
government to declare a general amnesty.
</P>
<P>
In a communique faxed to the Bonn bureau of Agence
France-Presse (AFP), the FIS urged all Algerian parties "to take
initiative, whatever the position you occupy on the national
territory, to announce a truce even in a unilateral way".
</P>
<P>
It called for the isolation of those who committed collective
killings and odious massacres of the innocent people and the
exposure of their conspiracies and silent collaborators.
(Algeria-FIS-Appeal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- The two houses of Thai parliament Saturday approved
Thailand's new constitution.
</P>
<P>
The constitution is aimed at granting more freedom to Thai
citizens and encouraging their participation in political realms,
making the country's politics and bureaucracy more transparent and
accountable to the citizens, and promoting stability of the
government, as well as restricting the authority of the prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
In a joint session of parliament, 578 lawmakers approved the
new constitution, the 16th in the country's history.
(Thailand-New Constitution)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PYONGYANG -- The Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
on Friday denounced the new Guidelines for Japan-U.S. Defense
Cooperation as a document meant for war.
</P>
<P>
The Korean Central News Agency said in an article on Friday
that the new Guidelines is a document aimed to reinforce the
activities of aggression of Japan and the United States in the
Asia-Pacific region, with the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea as their main target. (DPRK-Japan-Guidelines)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Two cargo vessels collided Friday night in the
Straits of Malacca with 28 crew members reportedly missing and
the search for the missing is continuing Saturday, according to
official sources.
</P>
<P>
The collision involving vessels -- N.V. Vickraman, registered
in Madras and Mount 1, registered in St Vincent, Caribbean, was
confirmed by Malaysian Deputy Transport Minister Ali Rustam
Saturday. (Malaysia-Vessel Collision)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The Bosnian Serb government has reached an
agreement with the United Nations on restructuring its police
force, U.N. special envoy Kai Eide said Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, Eide said the restructuring plan by the
Bosnian Serb authority submitted to the U.N. delegation was in
complete conformity with the requirements set in the Dayton peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the Serb police force will have its estimated
13,000 officers cut to 8,500 in maximum.
(Bosnia-Police-Reorganization) 
</P>
