<HEADLINE> Jordanian Minister: Wounded Hamas Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The wounded official of the
Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) in Amman is recovering and his
condition is "stable", a Jordanian minister said here today.
</P>
<P>
Khalid Mashiel, head of the political bureau Hamas in Amman,
was attacked by two Canadian tourists in front of his office in
Amman on Thursday and is now in the King Hussein Medical Center
(KHMC) for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian police detained those involved in the attack and
investigation was underway, Radio Jordan quoted Samir Mutawe,
Minister of state for Information, as saying.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the Hamas office in Amman accused the attack as an
assassination attempt by Mossad, the Israeli security department.
</P>
<P>
Mutawe said on Thursday that the incident was only the result
of a quarrel between Mashiel's driver and two Canadian tourists.
</P>
<P>
The attack on Mashiel happened amid increasing tension between
the Arabs and Israelis here after Israeli embassy guards were
attacked on Monday in Amman. Two Israeli security guards were
wounded and the criminals are still at large.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Ibrahim Ghosheh, Hamas spokesman in Amman,
was detained after he spoke to Reuters Television that the armed
struggle against Israel would continue.
</P>
<P>
Ghosheh made the remarks after the Izzedin Qassam Brigades, the
military wing of Hamas, claimed responsibility for the suicide
bombing attacks in Jerusalem in July and September, which killed 25
people and injured more than 300 others.
</P>
<P>
Hamas was established in 1987 to fight against Israel`s
occupation of Palestinian land. The Izzedin Qassam Brigades was
formed in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
