<HEADLINE> Iraq Protests Against U.S. Air Space Violation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Iraq lodged a strongly-worded
protest to the U.N. Security Council against the violations of the
Iraqi air space by a U.S. reconnaissance U2 plane, the Iraqi News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The protest was made in a message sent by Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister and Acting Minister of Foreign Affairs Tareq Aziz to Bill
Richardson, the U.N. Security Council chief for the current month.
</P>
<P>
The message urged the U.N. Security Council to reconsider the
breaches of the Iraq air space by the U.S. aircraft to spy on
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
This is in violation of the U.N. Charter on the sovereignty
of the member states and non-interference in their internal
affairs, said the message.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft that allegedly took off from the Saudi territories
for the first time in August, 1995, violated Iraqi air space for
over 375 times till the end of last August, according to the
message. 
</P>
</TEXT>
