<HEADLINE> New Political Party Formed in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 27 (Xinhua) -- A new political party,
the United Democratic Movement, was launched here today.
</P>
<P>
The new party, co-headed by former African National Congress
parliament member Bantu Holomisa and former National Party
General Secretary stalwart Roelf Meyer, is the first non-racial
party to have been formed in South Africa after the democratic
elections in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Among the party's aims and objectives is the "establishment of
a true South African constitutional democracy which rejects
racial domination of apartheid in reverse, which respects,
upholds and protects human dignity, life, liberty and the
prospertiy of its citizens".
</P>
<P>
The party also wants constitutional powers to be optimally
devoloped to the lowest possible sphere of government and
"preferably originally established at that level."
</P>
<P>
On civil order, it proposes that "people should be consulted
on the reimposition of the death penalty."
</P>
<P>
The government was opposed to the restoration of the death
penalty although there were cries for it owing to wide-spread
violence and crimes.
</P>
<P>
The new party urged the crackdown on crime.
</P>
<P>
"We are now in a very real sense experiencing a state of
emergency in the country on the question of crime and the
situation must be regarded and addressed as such," a policy
document of the party said.
</P>
<P>
The party also sets out its vision for South Africa's economy,
education, housing and health and welfare.
</P>
<P>
The official launch, held in the World Trade Center in Kempton
Park, was attended by 1,000 delegates and at least another 4,000
supporters from the nine provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
