<HEADLINE> French Anti-Terrorist Experts Consider GIA Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- French anti-terrorist experts
said today that the new threat posed by Algeria's extremist Armed
Islamic Group (GIA) was nothing new as it is neither precise nor
different from those published before by the extremist group.
</P>
<P>
The French military secret service Direction Generale de la
Surveillance Exterieure (DGSE) obtained a copy of the communique
by the GIA as early as Monday, and the DGSE was the only one to
judge the text as "worrying," said Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
In the communique published Friday in the London-based
underground bulletin of the GIA, "Al Ansar," the GIA claimed
responsibility for the massacres of civilians and threatened
France with new terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
While justifying the killings with religious terms, the GIA did
not claim responsibility for the latest massacre in Bentalha south
of Algiers, in which at least 200 civilians were slaughtered
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted unidentified anti-terrorist experts as saying that
the text's publication coincided with the questioning by British
police of Abu Hamza, the editor-in-chief of "Al Ansar," this week.
A French judge in charge of human rights issues also participated
in the questioning in London.
</P>
<P>
It also coincided with the second anniversary of the death of
Khaled Kelkal, one of the leaders of the Islamic network in Europe
which staged a wave of terrorist attacks in Paris and Lyon in
1995. Kelkal was shot dead by French military police on September
29, 1995.
</P>
<P>
Except a few subtle ways of presentation and a few phrases, the
text is strictly identical with those published by the GIA before,
said experts.
</P>
<P>
What is new about the text is its warning against the United
Nations, whose Secretary General Kofi Annan recently appealed for
tolerance and dialogue in Algeria. The GIA asked the United
Nations not to "follow the way of France."
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the new threat posed by the GIA against
France is "less serious" than the the letter addressed to
President Jacques Chirac on the eve of the 1996 Christmas, in
which the GIA threatened to launch attacks in France. The threats
were not followed up by action.
</P>
<P>
The French Interior Ministry also remains prudent over the
threat by the GIA although it said that the communique "seems to
be authentic." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
