<HEADLINE> Measles Breaks Out in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The Health Ministry of Sierra Leone
today confirmed a measles epidemic had broken out in the north of the
country.
</P>
<P>
A director in charge of disease control under the ministry
said that
some 3,000 cases of measles had been reported so far, according
to the British Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The official did not mention the death roll, but a report reaching
here said that at least 10 persons died of the disease in the past
three days, half of them children.
</P>
<P>
According to the director, the first case of measles was reported
in June this year and disease control teams, including one from the
United Nations Children's Fund, have been sent to the area.
</P>
<P>
There has been reports of short supply of daily necessities,
including medicines in Sierra Leone since west African countries
imposed sanctions after the May 25 coup that ousted the legitimate
government.
</P>
<P>
The situation has been worsened following the enforcement of the
economic embargo endorsed by the Economic Community of West African
States last month.  
</P>
