<HEADLINE> Cyprus Refutes Turkey's Claim on Missiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister
Ioannis Kasoulides today refuted Turkey's claims that S-300
defensive missile system can pose a threat to Turkey, Cyprus News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Replying to the speech of his Turkish counterpart, Ismail Cem,
at the 52nd U.N. General Assembly session, Kasoulides told the
U.N. General Assembly that "I want to categorically state that
these weapons are purely defensive surface-to-air missiles
destined to defend the small island of Cyprus from a potential
attack, since it has no military airport of its own."
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that the missiles will not be necessary if
there is substantial progress towards a Cyprus settlement or
agreement for the demilitarization of the island.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot government's decision to purchase and deploy
Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles in January has triggered
tension between the small island nation and Turkey which has
threatened to strike if the missiles are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Cem's statement that there are "two distinct
peoples, two separate administrations and two democracies" in
Cyprus, Kasoulides said this should not be the excuse of Turkey's
military presence on the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey sent troops and
took over 37 percent of the island following a failed pro-Athens
coup.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has maintained 35,000 troops in Turkish
Cypriot-controlled northern part which declared in 1983 a
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus " recognized only
by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides also dismissed Cem's claims that Cyprus can not join
the European Union (EU), by citing a recent statement by
Luxemburg's Foreign Minister and EU President, Jacques Poos, that
the 1960 treaties, establishing the Republic of Cyprus, do not
prevent it from joining the EU.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus applied for EU full membership in 1990. The EU has
decided to start accession talks with Cyprus early next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
