<DOCNO> XIE19970928.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Chirac Proposes Privileged EU-Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
has proposed the establishment of a "privileged partnership"
between Russia and European Union (EU) countries during his
three-day visit to Russia which ended today.
</P>
<P>
In a speech addressed to the students of the Institute of
International Relations in Moscow Friday, Chirac presented himself
as the main designer of such a partnership to the welcome of his
Russian hosts.
</P>
<P>
"I say to you with force that the European Union has the
vocation to be, in all the fields..., your primary partner. At the
dawn of the 21st century, it is a real association which should
progressively establish itself between Russia and the (European)
Union," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the mutual "opening between Eastern and
Western Europe is irreversible" and that "any division line should
be from now on excluded" in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no European security without Russia being fully
associated in it, giving it a profound consent and an active
participation," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
The new proposal by Chirac is in line with the French policy in
the field of European security, where Paris always utters a voice
of "dissent" among its Western partners of NATO.
</P>
<P>
When NATO planned to expand itself toward former Warsaw Pact
countries, Chirac proposed the signing of a charter on bilateral
relations between Russia and NATO before three Eastern European
countries -- Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary -- were
admitted by the Western military alliance.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was accepted by Russia and NATO and they signed
the treaty on bilateral relations in Paris on May 27 and
established the Russia-NATO Joint Council, which held its first
session in New York Friday.
</P>
<P>
During the NATO Madrid Summit in June, France refused to return
to the integrated military structure of NATO because of U.S.
refusal to hand over the Southern Command.
</P>
<P>
Chirac also announced in Moscow Friday that after France
completes the dismantling of its nuclear missile base in Albion,
southeastern France in 1999, no French nuclear warheads will be
targeted toward Russia.
</P>
<P>
These missiles were designed during the Cold War for quick
reaction strikes and can be fired within less than one minute.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the nuclear warheads carried by French navy
submarines and the Mirage 2000-N combat aircraft are not targeted
toward Russia either.
</P>
<P>
Chirac and Russian President Boris Yeltsin also reached total
agreement on reinforcing the role of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), the only forum gathering all
European countries and Russia.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to cooperate to encourage Arabs and Israel to
relaunch the Middle East peace process, and to help consolidate
peace in Bosnia through organization of elections in the country.
</P>
<P>
The daily Le Monde said that Chirac failed to recall in Moscow
that France has always supported NATO expansion and wants the
maintenance of the U.S. military presence in Europe although Paris
wishes to develop a European pillar within NATO by taking over the
Naples-based Southern Command of NATO.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin is completely opposed to NATO expansion and to American
interference in European security affairs.
</P>
<P>
"Europeans, and they alone, should with Russia ensure the
defense and security in Europe without any exterior interference,"
said Yeltsin during his meeting with Chirac. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
