<HEADLINE> Primakov Reiterates Opposition to More Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgini
Primakov has said that Moscow would not oppose expanding the
number of permanent seats in the United Nations Security Council
if only Germany alone was concerned, said German news reports
today.
</P>
<P>
Asked by the German newspaper Bild to comment on Bonn's bid for
a permanent seat in the UN Security Council, Primakov said, "If we
were talking about Germany alone, our answer would be yes." Russia
had attached special importance to the Russian-German relations,
he added.
</P>
<P>
But he also stressed that Russia was still against an
enlargement of the Security Council's permanent seats because such
a move would actually also involve several other countries. Such
an enlargement would make the UN less effective, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian foreign minister also reiterated Moscow's strong
opposition to NATO's (North Atlantic Treaty Organization) possible
expansion into the three Baltic states, saying that it would put
into question the good relations between NATO and Russia.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that the responsible politicians of NATO would be wise
enough," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
