<HEADLINE> Turkey Vows to Defend Its State Interests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Amid mounting tensions with
Greece, Turkish leaders voiced today that Turkey is determined to
defend its national interests.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a national maritime conference here, Turkish Prime
Minister Mesut Yilmaz said that Turkey will not remain
indifferent to its rights in the Aegean Sea, according to the
Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz stressed that Turkey will take action in the light of
the international law and practices.
</P>
<P>
On the current Cyprus missile crisis, the Turkish prime
minister reiterated that the Turkish government will use all
necessary means to block the deployment of the S-300 missiles
in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He said that Turkey will tighten security measures in its
air space and the Turkish Straits to abort the missile
transfer into Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"No country allows its shores and territorial waters to be
used against its own sovereignty and state security," Yilmaz
said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Cyprus signed an arms deal to buy about 150
anti-aircraft S-300 missiles from Russia, triggering strong
criticism from Ankara and Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has threatened that it will destroy these missiles
with force if they are finally deployed in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said
that the Aegean issue is a key problem for the Turkish-Greek
ties. adding that the two countries should rationally share the
waters and its resources.
</P>
<P>
"If this problem does not reach a just solution, the relations
between the two countries might become more tense," Ecevit
warned.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece has long been at odds over the sovereignty of
the Aegean sea and Cyprus issue. The dispute over an uninhabited
islet in the eastern Aegean that almost led to a war between the two
sides last year .
</P>
<P>
They pulled back their warships from the area following a
U.S. intervention, but the tensions between them remained.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Turkey accused Athens of encouraging the Cypriot
government to purchase Russian-made missiles, adding it would
negatively affect the settlement of the Cyprus issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
