<HEADLINE> Ireland Frees Five IRA Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The Irish government released
five Irish Republican Army (IRA) prisoners Friday night as its
response to the IRA cease-fire and Sinn Fein's participation in
the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
This followed the release of two other IRA men last month
before completion of their sentences in the high-security
Portlaoise prison, 50 miles from Dublin, according to reports
reaching here today from the capital.
</P>
<P>
The men released from Portlaoise prison were arrested on the
border of Donegal and Derry in 1992 for possessing assault rifles,
heavy machine guns and several hundred rounds of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
At least 35 IRA personnel were freed before the 1994
cease-fire, but the release program was abandoned after the London
Docklands bombing in February last year.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein welcomed Friday night's releases and called on the
British government to begin releasing all "political prisoners"
immediately.
</P>
<P>
Gerry Adams, Sinn Fein's president, raised the matter with
Bertie Ahern, the Irish prime minister, when they met in Dublin
last week.
</P>
<P>
Ian Paisley, the Democratic Unionist Party leader who refused
to join the peace talks next Monday, said Dublin had released the
IRA prisoners "to aid the IRA in wringing concessions from the
British government." 
</P>
