<HEADLINE> UK Public Opposed to Single Currency, Says Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 27 (Xinhua) - Most people in Britain remain
resolutely opposed to joining a single European currency,
according to a poll released today.
</P>
<P>
More than half the adult population, 57 percent, believed that
Britain should retain the pound even if other major European
powers launch the new currency on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Only 37 percent said they would like to join, said the poll
conducted by The Daily Telegraph.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe the poll will be a setback for ministers
urging Prime Minister Tony Blair to hold a referendum next year to
secure a mandate to sign up to a single currency.
</P>
<P>
Rumor that the British government is adopting a more positive
approach to the single currency caused a flurry of excitement on
the stock market and re-ignited the political debate over monetary
union.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 jumped by 160.8 points to hit an all-time record
of 5226.3. Soaring bond prices triggered a surge in the value of
bank shares which ended the day with gains of almost 10 percent as
institutional investors scrambled to get their hands on the
sector.
</P>
<P>
Late Friday, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook tried to
take the steam out of the rumor by saying "I think I can
authoritatively state that there will be no such announcement in
the immediate future."
</P>
<P>
Britain is due to make an announcement before the end of the
year on its approach to the European Monetary Union.
</P>
<P>
It is certain to confirm that Britain will not be in the first
wave of countries, led by France and Germany, initiating the
single currency at the start of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
