<HEADLINE> New Computer, Crewman Arrive at Dilapidated Mir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Atlantis crew pushed
through a new motion-control computer to replace the one that has
crashed three times in three weeks seconds after the hatches
between the space shuttle and Russia's decrepit Mir station swung
open Saturday, the NASA Space Center in Houston said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mir's new American crewman, David Wolf, told the
ground controllers that he was comfortable aboard the aging
station, his home for the next four months, as he woke up on the
shuttle Sunday morning and prepared for his big move into the
space station.
</P>
<P>
Atlantis, carrying the 41-year-old doctor-engineer and six
others, pulled up and docked earlier as Mir's central computer
held it steady at a crucial time.
</P>
<P>
When the Atlantis crew members entered the station, they were
greeted with hugs, handshakes and smiles from Foale, who has spent
four and a half months on Mir, and his two Russian crewmates.
</P>
<P>
The crews will carry water, food, plugs for holes, pressurized
air tanks and other important gear from Atlantis to the station
during the six days of links. 
</P>
</TEXT>
