<HEADLINE> Israel to Return More Revenues to PNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today said he has ordered the release of more
withheld revenues to the Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
At an urgent cabinet meeting, Netanyahu instructed the Finance
Ministry to speed up the return of the taxes Israel had collected
for the PNA in response to PNA's crackdown on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He also said the security cooperation between both sides are
expected to resume after a six-month suspension.
</P>
<P>
PNA had recently stepped up its efforts to fight terrorism and
taken actions against Hamas and its infrastructure, he told the
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The release will free about half of the tax revenues it had
refused to transfer to the PNA since the two suicide bombings in
Jerusalem which killed 20 Israelis and the five bombers.
</P>
<P>
The amount is expected to reach 17 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, Israeli punitive closure of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip have dealt a cut-throat blow to Palestinian economy, which
suffered losses of up to several million dollars every day.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians urged Natanyahu to lift the blockade which
barred tens of thousands of them from reaching their jobs.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the cabinet meeting also discuss the
impact of a nationwide general strike organized by the Israeli
Federation of Trade Unions (Histadrut) today.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu sharply criticized Histadrut for the strike, which he
claimed could cause huge losses to the economy, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The general strike started at 6:00 am local time and ended at
14:00 pm today, involving various sectors of the Israeli economy.
But it was continuing this afternoon in sectors which were not
crucial to the public, according to Histadrut officials.
</P>
<P>
Histadrut was angered by government-proposed new budget cuts to
the pension funds and a general restructuring of the economy. It
is feared that privatization of state-owned corporations will lead
to serious unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Histadrut requested the government to honor an existing
agreement on pension signed in 1995 by the then leaders of the
government and trade unions.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu government, however, refused to recognize the
agreement, which it says is not binding.
</P>
<P>
Today's cabinet meeting focused on ways to solve this problem,
but Israel Radio did not elaborate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
