<HEADLINE> Japan, Ningxia of China to Intensify Exchanges, Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Former Japanese Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita said here today that Japan is willing to
intensify exchanges and cooperation in various fields of economic
and social development with northwest China's Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Takeshita, who is here to mark the 25th anniversary of the
normalization of diplomatic relations between China and Japan,
made the remarks during a meeting with Bai Lichen, chairman of
the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Regional government.
</P>
<P>
Covering an area of 66,400 square kilometers, Ningxia is the
largest habitat of the Hui ethnic group in China. One third of the
region's 5.22 million population are Hui.
</P>
<P>
A native of Shimane Prefecture in Japan, Takeshita visited
China for many times, making great contributions to the
improvement of the Sino-Japanese relations and the friendship
between the Chinese and Japanese peoples.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to his efforts, Ningxia and Shimane established
brotherly relations in October 1993, starting various types of
friendly exchanges and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Bai told Takeshita that over the past four decades since the
founding of the autonomous region, especially since the beginning
of China's reform and opening-up drive, Ningxia has witnessed
rapid economic growth, all-round social progress and solid ethnic
unity.
</P>
<P>
To date, he said, the region has developed economic and trade
relations and technical cooperation with over 60 countries and
regions in the world, and has more than 400 foreign-funded
enterprises, many of them with Japanese investment.
</P>
<P>
However, he conceded that Ningxia still is one of China's
underdeveloped regions due to its weak economic foundation, and
that part of the region's rural population in the southern
mountainous areas remains extremely poor because of a serious
water shortage.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, the cooperation between Ningxia and Japan
has broad prospects. He hoped that Takeshita could use his high
prestige in Japan's political and financial circles to seek
benefits for the people of Ningxia.
</P>
<P>
Takeshita responded that with apparent advantages in energy
reserves and agricultural sector, rich cultural heritage and the
local government's emphasis on education, Ningxia surely has a
great future.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past several years, Ningxia and Shimane have achieved
remarkable progress in multi-level exchanges and cooperation," he
said. "I'm glad to further promote the friendly relationship
between Japan and China, as well as between my hometown and
Ningxia."
</P>
<P>
He also highly praised Ningxia's investment environment, saying
that economic cooperation between Japan and Ningxia has great
potential.
</P>
<P>
"After my return to Japan, I will describe Ningxia in detail to
the Japanese business people to help further expand our
cooperation," he promised.  
</P>
</TEXT>
