<HEADLINE> Residential Housing Wins Market in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Though they have lived in
inexpensive public housing for decades, more and more Chinese want
to buy their own apartments, and with the deepening of housing
reform they're getting the chance.
</P>
<P>
This mindset is especially prevalent in Shenzhen, a showcase
for China's reform and opening-up drive in south China's Guangdong
province; about 82 percent of the residents there have opted to
buy rather than rent.
</P>
<P>
Home ownership is gaining popularity across the nation. In
Nanjing, eastern Jiangsu province, almost half of the marketable
public housing had sold by June. Young Hainan island province,
also in south China, had sold 70 percent, and the Shijiazhuang
city in northern Hebei province, more than 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
China's residential housing was not for sale until a few years
ago. As a major part of the socialist welfare system, it was
allocated for residents to rent but tradable on the market.
</P>
<P>
"We used to regard living comfortably in public houses at a low
rent as one of the great advantages of socialist society," said
one recent house buyer.
</P>
<P>
In April 1980, the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping put
forward an outline for housing reform, and the state government
then decided to push the public houses on the market in a bid to
boost urban housing construction and meet the demands of growing
population.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970928.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residential Housing Wins Market in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After a series of experiments with housing reform measures and
numerous national conferences on the subject, the central
government unveiled a State Council decision calling for a new
urban housing system be set up before the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the country has to establish a public housing fund
system, deepen the reform in the renting of public houses, sell
public houses gradually, boost the real estate market and a market
for housing maintenance, and accelerate the building of urban
residential houses.
</P>
<P>
The people across China have warmly welcomed the reforms.
</P>
<P>
The first group of house buyers were granted various price
reductions, and the money saved was pooled to build new apartments
for others.
</P>
<P>
Residents in Shenzhen now are allotted an average of 14.2
square meters living space per head; the urban dwellers in Hainan
enjoy more than 15 sq. m. of floor space on average, and more than
half are living comfortably in well-furnished and equippeds
apartments.
</P>
<P>
The nation aspires to have an average per capita living space
of nine sq. m. by the year 2000, according to the Vice-Minister of
Construction Ye Rushang.
</P>
<P>
China put more than 1.1 trillion yuan into the building of 1.4
billion sq. m. of urban residential housing between 1991 and
1996. In 1990, the average living space for urban dwellers went up
to 8.47 sq. m., from the 6.77 sq. m.
</P>
<P>
The financial sector in China also provided solid support for
the marketing of the residential housing. The secured bank loans
from the Industrial and Commercial Bank of China, for example,
have helped numerous eager house buyers move into new apartments.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
