<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haze Emergency in Sarawak Revoked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The state of haze
emergency, declared in East Malaysia's Sarawak on September 19,
was lifted today following significant improvement in Air
Pollutant Index (API) readings.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar
Ibrahim in Kuching, capital of Sarawak State, according to the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
Anwar told a news conference there that he signed the letter
for the lifting of the haze emergency today and it took effect
immediately.
</P>
<P>
Sarawak has so far been the most badly affected state by the
haze in the country with the API in the state once touching a high
of 851.
</P>
<P>
The haze emergency, the first in Malaysia, was declared by its
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad after the Air Pollutant Index
(API) in Kuching breached the 600 mark, far beyond the 301-500
hazardous level.
</P>
<P>
But the situation improved over the past few days with API
reading dipping to 107 at 8am today, and by 11am today, further to
99 before reaching an all time low of 83 at 5pm today, which is
considered "moderate".
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that all schools and offices which were ordered
closed under the emergency would reopen as usual from tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
He, however, advised the people to continue wearing masks or
cover their nose with a wet towel to prevent from inhaling the
polluted air.
</P>
<P>
Anwar also called on the people to tune in to the radio for the
latest API readings to know the haze situation in their area.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the air quality in the country as a whole showed
slight improvement in late afternoon compared to earlier in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
The API readings of 13 areas including Kuala Lumpur still fell
within the unhealthy level category.  
</P>
</TEXT>
