<HEADLINE> CPPCC, United Front Dept of CPC Central Committee Host National Day Reception  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- More than 700 people,
including compatriots from the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR), Macao and Taiwan and overseas Chinese and Chinese
nationals residing overseas joined a grand reception here this
evening to mark the founding anniversary of the People's Republic
of China.
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan, a Standing Committee member of the Political Bureau
of the Communist Party of China (CPC)'s Central Committee and also
chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), attended the reception,
which was held in the Great Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the group, Ye Xuanping, vice-chairman of the
CPPCC National Committee, first extended sincere greetings to all
the guests, people of various ethnic groups and circles across
China, Taiwan, Hong Kong SAR and Macao compatriots and other
overseas Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Ye said that over the past 48 years, tremendous changes have
taken place in China, and that the country's reform, opening-up
and modernization drive, under the guidance of Deng Xiaoping
Theory, has scored remarkable achievements that have drawn
worldwide attention since the Third Plenum of the 11th CPC Central
Committee.
</P>
<P>
He described the 15th National Congress of the CPC, which was
convened here from September 12-18, as an epoch-making event that
summarized the past experience and ushered in a promising future.
</P>
<P>
He said that the congress's election of a new central
leadership with Jiang Zemin at the core would serve as a strong
guarantee for China's unity and stability and the vigorous
development of the country's various undertakings.
</P>
<P>
"We are firmly convinced that the Communist Party of China will
unite people of various ethnic groups across the country, and lead
them to forge ahead for an all-round advancement of the great
cause of building socialism with Chinese characteristics into the
21st century," he added.
</P>
