<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian-U.S. Accords An Important Step in Arms Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The signing of a package of
Russian-U.S. disarmament accords is the most important step in the
course of arms control, said Russian Foreign Ministry today.
</P>
<P>
An announcement, made by the Press Bureau of the Foreign
Ministry, said the accords are in the interests of Russia's
security and in conformity with Russia's economic situation.
</P>
<P>
The accords highlighted the two countries' willingness to go
along with further reductions in strategic nuclear weapons and
created favorable conditions for Russia to implement START II,
reported the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright signed the accords
with her Russian counterpart Yevgeni Primakov in New York when
attending the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The accords include an adaptation of the 1972 anti-ballistic
missile (ABM) treaty that limits the capability of both countries'
anti-missile weapons. They also include an accord that postpones
to December 31, 2007 the date at which the START II treaty has to
be put into effect, instead of December 31, 2003.
</P>
<P>
START II, signed in January 1993 by Russia and the United
States, already has been ratified by the U.S. Senate but not by
the Russian Duma because it fears that Washington would break the
ABM pact by deploying multiple anti-missile defensive systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970928.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
