<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEM Calls for Closer Ties Between Asia, Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Economic ministers from Asian
and European countries concluded today their first meeting in
Chiba, near Tokyo, and called for closer ties between the two
continents for sustainable growth.
</P>
<P>
To expand trade and investment flows between the two regions,
the ministers from 25 Asian and European countries set principles
and common policy tasks at the two-day session of the Asian-Europe
Meeting (ASEM).
</P>
<P>
In a chairman's statement issued after the meeting, the
ministers said ASEM economic cooperation will "reinforce the
underlying sound economic structures" and "contribute to the
robustness of the ASEM economies."
</P>
<P>
"In this context, ministers expressed the view that transient
economic difficulties, export slowdown and exchange rate
fluctuations observed in some ASEM partners would not harm the
significant long-term potential of these economies," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers "affirmed their confidence in the strong future
prospects of these economies" in an era of globalization, taking
into account positive factors such as abundant investment
opportunities and high savings rates, it added.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also stressed in the statement to cooperate in
guaranteeing energy safety, protecting environment and
accomplishing sustainable economic growth, which, they said, are
the common tasks.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the first since ASEM was launched last
year, the economic ministers agreed on five principles for
enhanced economic cooperation between Asia and Europe, including
"nondiscriminatory liberalization, transparency and open
regionalism" and "consistency and compliance with international
rules."
</P>
<P>
They also set three policy goals, namely "greater economic
interaction between enterprises," "improvement of the business
environment toward increased trade and investment" and "sustained
and stable economic growth."
</P>
<P>
The economic ministers noted Asia's large demands on power,
gas, transportation, communication and water treatment in the next
decade and agreed that infrastructure is important to the further
development of Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
To promote investment flows between the two regions, the
ministers endorsed an Investment Promotion Action Plan for
enhanced disclosure of investment-related data.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed on the framework for a Trade Facilitation
Action Plan to be adopted by ASEM leaders at their second summit
in London in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
ASEM was created in March 1996 with the aim to establish closer
relations between the two regions.
</P>
<P>
The forum groups Brunei, China, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, South Korea, Thailand, Vietnam of Asia,
and Europe's Austria, Belgium, Britain, Denmark, Germany, Greece,
Finland, France, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands,
Portugal, Spain and Sweden as well as the European Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
