<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deng Xiaoping Theory And Shanghai University Students (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 28 (Xinhua) -- While many older Chinese
find it hard to see eye to eye with today's modern-minded youth,
Deng Xiaoping, who saw it all in China in his 93 years, now seems
to have a lot in common with young people.
</P>
<P>
This is particularly true for the 140,000 university students
in Shanghai, a major stop during Deng's tour of southern China in
1992, when he gave famous and important remarks on the country's
need to deepen reform and open up further to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is the first Chinese city in which universities have
offered a special course on Deng Xiaoping Theory. Since 1994, 34
of the municipality's 40 universities have included the class in
their curricula, and many students have organized their own small
study groups to discuss the late paramount leaders ideology.
</P>
<P>
When the course opened in East China Engineering University,
1,800 students signed up in the first semester, setting a school
record for the number of students taking a selective courses.
</P>
<P>
When the third volume of the Selected Works of Deng Xiaoping
was published in Shanghai, the book soon became a bestseller on
Shanghai campuses.
</P>
<P>
Han Junyi, a fifth-grade student from Shanghai Medical Sciences
University who has read over 20 books about Deng's theory and his
life, said, "Deng's theory has brought earth-shattering changes to
China. We university students are deeply interested not only in
the theory but also by the great man's characteristics and his
legendary life experiences."
</P>
<P>
Four thousand and five hundred students in Shanghai Normal
University, making up over 94 percent of the school's total
student body, turned in essays when the school authority announced
papers on the study of Deng Xiaoping theory were being accepted.
</P>
<P>
Yang Longbo, a senior from Shanghai Normal University, said,
"It is a wonderful thing that Deng Xiaoping Theory was included in
the Party constitution during the 15th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China."
</P>
<P>
Yang has spent three years studying Deng's books, and has
written quite a few theses on the basis of her understanding of
the them.
</P>
<P>
Yang, a native of a once poor village in Chongming County on
the outskirts of Shanghai, is deeply impressed by Deng's idea that
"Poverty is not socialism."
</P>
<P>
"Poverty had forced many people in my hometown to beg for a
living," she said, "but since China's reform and opening-up in the
late 1970s, beggars are nowhere to be found, and now all families
have built their own houses and installed telephones and hot water
heater and use liquefier."
</P>
<P>
"All these changes would have been impossible if it weren't for
Deng Xiaoping Theory," Yang noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970928.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deng Xiaoping Theory And Shanghai University Students (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Deng Xiaoping and his theory have created opportunities for
these university students to realize their ambitions, which their
parents and grandparents had no way to get when they were young,"
said Cheng Weili, deputy director of the Deng Xiaoping Theory
Research Center of the Shanghai Academy of Social Sciences, when
explaining why contemporary university students are so interested
in Deng Xiaoping Theory.
</P>
<P>
He added that the young people also get to know the major trend
of the country's development in the 21st century by studying Deng
Xiaoping Theory, which provides answers to their various questions.
</P>
<P>
Some experts deem that college kids' interest in Deng Xiaoping
Theory is greatly due to the fact that it has stood the test of
time during China's development process.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey by the State Education Commission shows that 92
percent of the college and university students in Shanghai agree
that the central government's policies of further carrying out
reforms and opening still widerly to the outside world have
produced remarkable achievements.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that 95 percent of the students have read
the Selected Works of Deng Xiaoping, and 97 percent share the view
that Deng Theory can guide China's reform and opening-up as well
as the country's modernization drive.  
</P>
</TEXT>
