<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weizman Urges Netanyahu to Advance Peace March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman
today urged Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to do his utmost to
propel the Middle East peace process that has been stuck for over
six months.
</P>
<P>
Weizman made the appeal in Egypt's seaport city of Alexandria
at a joint press conference with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak. The two leaders had emerged from talks on ways to revive
the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Weizman arrived in Alexandria this morning on a brief visit to
Egypt, just a few days after Netanyahu posted plans to construct
300 new housing units in the West Bank town of Efrat, a move that
added fuel to Palestinian outrage and drew opposition even from
the United States government.
</P>
<P>
Weizman told reporters that he discussed with Mubarak on the
imperativeness that Netanyahu begin to work for progress of the
peace march. He said his aim of directing this call to Netanyahu
is to serve the regional peace drive.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that Egypt will play a positive and
continuous role in peace making in the region.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said Egypt is ready to mediate between Syria and the
Jewish state for a resumption of talks that froze in February 1996
and urged Israel to take "concrete steps" so that Syria could act
correspondingly.
</P>
<P>
Syria insists that Israel return the Golan Heights it captured
in 1967 in exchange for peace as promised by Israel's former Labor
government.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Mubarak praised Weizman as an
"advocate of peace".
</P>
<P>
He said today's meeting centered on the Mideast peace process
and on finding ways to restart the disrupted talks, adding they
have touched up all the issues of concern to the two countries and
the region as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian and Israeli peace teams are holding talks in
Washington in what may be their last chance to save the crumbling
peace process. Weizman himself will go to the U.S. capital for
talks with President Bill Clinton before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
The Mideast peace process came to a standstill in March after
Israel decided to go ahead with Jewish settlement expansion in
East Jerusalem. It slid into deeper crisis after two suicide
bombings ripped off Jerusalem markets in July and September ,
killing 25 people including the five bombers.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu government took suffocating punitive measures
against Palestinians and insisted that primary concern be given to
Israel's security. It announced to stop giving back lands to
Palestinians as stipulated by their accords as long as they fell
short of its demand to crack down on terrorist infrastructure.
</P>
</TEXT>
