<HEADLINE> Sampras Defends His No.1 in Grand Slam Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Peter Sampras of the United
States made amends for his disappionting performance in the
U.S. Open by a triumph in the final of the Grand Slam Cup on
Sunday in Munich, Germany.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, ranked No.1 in the world, won in strainght sets with
6-2, 6-4, 7-5 over the No.3 Patrick Rafter of Australia to earn
the 1.5 million U.S. dollars prize.
</P>
<P>
Rafter, who defeated Czech Petr Korda in a four hour, 17 minute
marathon on Saturday, made no answer to Sampras' better form.
Sampras scored 5-0 before the Australian, champion of this year's
U.S. Open, took his serve and broke. But he was broken again and
lose the set.
</P>
<P>
Rafter steadily held his serves in the second set before he
broken at 4-4 and Sampras took the set on his serve.
</P>
<P>
Rafter made a great performance in the U.S. Open, which allowed
him in the Grand Slam Cup for the first in his career. But he has
now lost his last six matches to Sampras.
</P>
<P>
Sampras also got a 500,000 U.S. dollars bonus for winning
Wimbledon and the Australian Open to double his earnings for the
year.
</P>
<P>
Rafter earned one million dollars, including 750,000 dollars
for reaching the final and a bonus as U.S. Open champion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
