<HEADLINE> Fighting Rages around Afghan Northern Major City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Fighting between the Afghan
Islamic Taliban militia and their rival northern alliance were
continuing to rage today around Mazar-e-Sharif, around 300 km
north of the Afghan capital of Kabul, Pakistan Television (PTV)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Taliban fighters have consolidated their positions around
Mazar-e-Sharif, the seat of the anti-Taliban northern alliance,
following fresh attack, PTV quoted a Taliban spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chief of the Taliban Supreme Council Mohammad Omar
today urged the opposition forces defending Mazar-e-Sharif to lay
down their arms, PTV said.
</P>
<P>
If the anti-Taliban elements in Mazar-e-Sharif surrender, they
would be given general amnesty, Omar announced today in Kandahar,
Taliban's stronghold in southern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Omar also asked the neighboring countries not to provide asylum
and not to give transport facilities to the leaders of the
northern alliance comprising forces loyal to Uzbek warlords Rashid
Dostum and Abdul Malik, and Afghanistan's former military chief
Ahmad Masood and the Shiite Hezb-e-Wadhat.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban have claimed they had made major gains around
Mazar-e-Sharif and their fighters have seized areas within 15 km
of the Afghanistan's second largest city. However, the claim has
not been independently confirmed so far.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three weeks, Mazar-e-Sharif has been under
Taliban attack.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who now control two-thirds of the Afghan territory
and the capital of Kabul, briefly controlled Mazar-e-Sharif
airport early this month but were forced to retreat in a few days.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban alliance, who announced Mazar-e-Sharif as
their capital, has been battling the hard-line militia in
northern, central and western Afghanistan since the Taliban seized
Kabul last September.  
</P>
</TEXT>
