<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Party Official Stresses Priority of Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, September 28 (Xinhua) -- A senior Party official
said here recently that China would continue to attach top
priority to agriculture, the foundation and guarantee for
realizing the country's strategic goal for economic restructuring
and development.
</P>
<P>
Wen Jiabao, a member of the Political Bureau and the
Secretariat of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of
China (CPC), made the remarks during a five-day tour in the rural
areas of northeast China's Jilin Province. He concluded his tour
today.
</P>
<P>
"The 15th CPC National Congress has decided to continue
regarding agriculture as the top priority in the economic work,
and to further strengthen the country's agricultural foundation,"
Wen told local officials.
</P>
<P>
The congress, the last to be held by the CPC in this
century, was convened in Beijing from September 12-18.
</P>
<P>
Wen noted that the smooth development of rural economy and
bumper grain harvests over the past several years
have served as a strong guarantee for China's reform and
opening-up drive and national economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"To achieve the strategic goal set by the 15th CPC National
Congress for our country's economic restructuring and growth still
needs the strong support from the agricultural sector," he said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to list a series of measures to promote agricultural
development, which include maintaining the consistency of the
Party's basic policies in rural areas, further deepening rural
reforms, improving agricultural infrastructure, and invigorating
the agricultural sector by popularizing scientific and technical
achievements.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of promoting socialist ethical and
cultural progress in the vast rural areas, adding that grassroots
Party organizations and the system of democratic election and
management in the countryside should be further strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Wen also visited farmers in western Jilin afflicted
by serious drought earlier this year, urging local officials to
take good care of those farmers' life.
</P>
<P>
One of China's major grain producers, Jilin now provides some
one tenth of the country's total grain output. Last year the
province scored a record grain harvest. 
</P>
