<HEADLINE> US Offers Egypt 266 Million Dollars in Grants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The United States signed here
today with Egypt eight agreements totalling 266 million
U.S. dollars as part of its 1997 aid program for the largest Arab
country in the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreements, the grant will be earmarked to
support Egypt's private enterprises, assist the reform of power
sector and help improve health care services.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony was attended by U.S. Ambassador to Egypt
Edward Walker, U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID)
Acting Director Toni Chritiansen-Wagner and Egyptian Minister of
State for Planning and International Cooperation Zafer el-Beshri.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the two countries will sign several other aid
agreements worth 183.5 million dollars. This will bring the total
value of agreements signed between the two sides during
January-September period of 1997 to 809 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Since Egypt signed the U.S.-brokered Camp David peace accords
with Israel in 1979, it has been the second largest beneficiary
of the U.S. assistance after Israel, with an annual sum of 2.1
billion dollars which includes 1.3 billion dollars in military
aid and 815 million dollars in economic aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
