<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: UDM, Black Horse in S. African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 28 (Xinhua) -- While major political
parties started their active preparations for the 1999 general
elections, United Democratic Movement (UDM), a newly set up
party, is also throwing its weight on the political competition
in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The UDM, launched Saturday in Johannesburg, has apparently
drawn great attention from the people in the country, as it is
the first political party co-chaired by black and white people
since the first non-racial elections in 1994.
</P>
<P>
There are two top leaders in the party. One is Bantu Holomisa,
popular leader who fell out of favor with the ruling African
National Congress (ANC), and the other is Roelf Meyer, who quit
the white-dominated National Party earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Addressing delegates at the launch of the new party, Meyer
said the UDM would be "the political home of all South Africans",
saying, "We no longer want to vote for political parties that
have taken root in a soil of racial division." He stressed the
need to foster a strong multi-party democracy in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
To promote national unity and to realize the real multi-party
democracy are the most resonant and attractive slogans put
forward by the UDM.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, once known for its notorious policy of racial
segregation, abolished apartheid laws right after the 1994
general elections, and set up an ANC-led Government of National
Unity which included the National Party.
</P>
<P>
However, the National Party headed by Deputy President F.W. de
Klerk, pulled out of the central government in June last year due
to its sharp political differences with the ANC coalition, which
also included the South African Communist Party and the Congress
of South African Trade Union.
</P>
<P>
Opposition claimed that ever since the National Party's
withdrawal from the government, the ANC, which is the largest
black party in South Africa, has in reality become the sole
dominator in the country. A new kind of racial discrimination is
being practised by ANC, the extremists charged.
</P>
<P>
Observers believed that the UDM is trying to give a signal
that it is promoting a truly multi-party democracy, thus creating
an image that would be accepted both by the black, the white and
the colored people in the country.
</P>
<P>
Another remarkable characteristic of the UDM is that it pays
special attention to various national thorny issues like social
security, crime and employment.
</P>
<P>
Holomisa said South Africa "is in a state of disarray, not as
a result of the past government's policies, but the inability of
the present government to direct resources to appropriate social
programs and get its priorities right."
</P>
<P>
Meyer pledged his party's support for the war against crime
and corruption, saying South Africa needs to become
"criminal-hostile to the greatest possible extent".
</P>
<P>
Referring to his aspiration, Meyer said the UDM would devoted
itself "to making South Africa a world-class nation in 10 years
time".
</P>
<P>
A survey suggests there is a floating vote of 25 percent who
might support a party like the UDM. Part of the reason for this
is that the party starts with a clean slate. It is not mired in
deeds and attitudes of the past.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said although the UDM is by now a minority party
in South Africa, it is very much likely to be hard challenger
among the ruling ANC and opposition parties because it strongly
advocates more jobs, less crime and a better life for all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970928.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Peace Bloc Launches Boycott Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Israeli peace organization
Gush Shalom (Israeli Peace Bloc) today announced to lauch a
boycott campaign against products of Jewish settlements in the
occupied territories in an effort to save the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference here, Gush Shalom leader Uri
Avnery said that the boycott campaign is "the means of defense
of the people of Israel against the settlement, and most of all
against the intent of a small minority in Israel to impose its
will on the great majority."
</P>
<P>
"If you believe that settlement building is a danger to
Israel and a step toward the war, the way to avert it is very
simple: put back settlement products on the shelf," Avnery said.
</P>
<P>
Avnery said that his organization is launching a propaganda
campaign to teach people how to identify settlement products,
and how to contact with Gush Shalom for a list of these products
by phone or by E-mail.
</P>
<P>
Oren Medicks, head of the Gush Shalom committee in charge of
the boycott campaign, announced a series of measures to be taken
in the next few months to get the capmaign to full proportion.
</P>
<P>
He said that Gush Shalom would publish more advertisements in
local newspapers, issuing stickers to customers in supermarkets
and advising customers to avoid buying settlement products.
</P>
<P>
More important is, Medicks told Xinhua, that Gush Shalom had
begun negotiations with diplomats from the European Community
(EU) in an attempt to persuade these countries to stop importing
settlement products from Israel, because European market is the
leading export market for these products.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that the boycott campaign faced great
difficulties in making it a big success, mainly because some of
the agricultural products, including flowers, exported under the
marks of "Made in Israel" without listing the origins of
production.
</P>
<P>
Israel's settlement activities are the outstanding barrier in
the path to push forward the Israeli-Palestinian peace process,
which has been stalled since March when Israel began building
the Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
