<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insurance Industry Bleeds at False Health Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 28 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's
insurance companies stand to lose millions of Rand annually as
HIV carriers and AIDS sufferers are being given clean bills of
health when applying for life cover, Sunday Tribune said today.
</P>
<P>
Medical personnel, including specialists -- particularly in
KwaZulu-Natal -- allegedly switched blood samples so that tests
on HIV (human immunodeficiency virus) positive patients were
reported to be negative, thus enabling the patients to make
successful applications for life assurance, the paper quoted
medical sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Some doctors have allegedly changed the cause of death from
HIV to other complications not associated with the fatal virus.
</P>
<P>
Other important papers such as medical examination forms have
been allegedly falsified and doctors have been known to turn a
blind eye to them, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
"Assurance companies often see piles of forms in which
patients have the same height and weight registered," said Pieter
Coetzer, committee member of the Life Officers Association
representing life assurance companies.
</P>
<P>
Spokesmen for insurance industry giants like Old Mutual and
Sanlam Life have expressed grave concern at what is threatening
to become a huge and financially disastrous scam for the
industry.
</P>
<P>
"It's of great concern to us because when fraudulent claims
are made, other policy holders are adversely affected," Sanlam
Life spokesman Nico Van Gijsen said.
</P>
<P>
AIDS (acquired immunodeficiency syndrome) was spreading
quickly in South Africa. According to statistics last year, about
1.5 million people were infected with the deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
Experts predicted that 5 million people would be infected with
HIV which causes AIDS by the year 2000.
South Africa has a population of some 41 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
