<HEADLINE> Sino-Nepalese Economic Cooperation Forum Opens in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Second Sino-Nepalese
Non-Governmental Economic Cooperation Forum opened in the
Great Hall of the People in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the two-day meeting are scheduled to review the
work of the forum in the past year, study its prospects and plans,
discuss regional economic cooperation between China and Nepal as
well as other southern Asian countries, and boost border trade
between China's Tibet and Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Entrepreneurs from China and Nepal will also negotiate on some
projects in the sectors of hydropower, light industry, handicraft,
textile, electronics and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Jing Shuping, president of the All-China Federation of Industry
and Commerce, said in his opening speech that the forum is a new
tool to boost the bilateral relations and economic cooperation
between China and Nepal.
</P>
<P>
It not only gives play to the non-governmental forces in
developing relations between countries, but also shows China's and
Nepal's confidence in increasing cooperation, he added.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jian, assistant foreign-minister of China, and Yubaraj
Singh Pradhan, Nepalese Ambassador to China, also delivered
speeches on behalf of their respective governments.
</P>
<P>
The forum was sponsored by the Chinese and Nepalese governments
and organized by the All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce
and the Nepalese Federation of Industry and Commerce. The first
forum was held in Kathmandu, the Nepalese capital, in October
1996. 
</P>
