<HEADLINE> Rwandan Forces Return From Congo: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Most of the Rwandan troops
have withdrawn from the neighboring Democratic Republic of Congo
where it helped to topple former Zairian President Mobutu Sese
Seko, Rwandan President Pasteur Bizimungu said today.
</P>
<P>
A report from Rwandan capital Kigali quoted Bizimungu as
saying that only a few defense experts from Rwanda have remained
behind to train the army of Congolese President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
"We have pulled the bulk of our forces back home. While in
Congo, we technically assisted the Congolese to liberate
themselves," Bizimungu told Reuters in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
"Only a few of our military people remain in Congo as
advisors, very few of them," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports disclosed that more than 1,000 Rwandan troops
involved in Kabila's seven-month military drive to topple
Mobutu.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda was the backbone of an international and regional
alliance against Mobutu, who died in Rabat early this month.
</P>
<P>
Regional military sources said that Uganda and Angola, among
others, also actively took part in the war against Mobutu.
</P>
<P>
They claimed that other countries such as South Africa and the
United States provided Kabila with diplomatic and political
muscle.
</P>
<P>
Kabila's rebellion, began in October last year and ended on
May 17 when his forces took Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan Vice-President and Defense Minister Major-General Paul
Kagame admitted in July that Rwandana soldiers joined Kabila's
uprising directly against Mobutu, but other Rwandan and Congolese
officials remain reticent about the military ties between the two
states.
</P>
<P>
Kagame had said Rwanda provided training and arms for the
rebel forces in the then Zaire even before the push to overthrow
Mobutu began in October.
</P>
<P>
Bizimungu said his army is now engaged in operations to
stamp out pockets of insecurity in some parts of his country,
caused by Hutu refugees returning from Congo, or ex Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Over a million Rwandan Hutus streamed into the former
Zaire in 1994, fearing reprisals for the genocide of minority
Tutsis by militant Hutus.
</P>
<P>
About 600,000 Hutus returned to Rwanda late last year after
their camps were shelled allegedly by Rwandan forces, while the
U.N. says others are unaccounted for, presumed dead or still
wondering across Congo's vast jungle.
</P>
<P>
Bizimungu claimed that some of the refugees are involved in
organized acts of violence against the army and Tutsi civilians.
But Bizimungu, himself a Hutu, said the insurgency has been
contained by his army.
</P>
<P>
"The insecurity is localized in the northwest. The rest of
the country is secure and completely safe," Bizimungu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
