<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Build Most Secure Prison in World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 28 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is to
build one of the most secure prisons in the world in
KwaZulu-Natal in the next 18 months, the Sunday Tribune newspaper
said today.
</P>
<P>
The Super Maximum Prison (SPM), to be built in Kokstad in the
eastern province, will match the highest security prison in the
United States at Boulder, Colorado, and then go a step or two
further, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The SPM is expected to cost 250 million Rand (53 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Goltz Wessmann, special adviser to Minister of Correctional
Services Sipo Mzimela, said the Kokstad prison will be one of the
most secure institutions in the world.
</P>
<P>
"It will be a very secure facility. That is why it will cost
about 250 million Rand. But over a 10-year period it could prove
to be the cheapest prison if there are no escapes. Escapes are
very costly," he said.
</P>
<P>
Escapes are frequent in South African jails. In the 15 months
as of March this year, more than 4,240 prisoners slipped from
their cells.
</P>
<P>
Escapes were blamed on corruption of warders and activities of
drug syndicates.
</P>
<P>
In order to address the problem, Mzimela officially opened
South Africa's first closed maximum security prison (CMAX) in
Pretoria on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Inmates in the CMAX, which houses criminals with violent
records, escapees and those who killed fellow inmates or police
staff, will be locked in their cells for 23 hours a day and will
always be cuffed outside their cells.
</P>
<P>
The CMAX is regarded as a guinea pig for the planned Kokstad
prison.
</P>
<P>
The SPM will be built in a cross, block or butterfly shape
surrounded by a section of no-man's land and two or three wire
fences with the first one being electrified to set off alarms and
video surveillance.
</P>
<P>
The prison security system will be driven by computers and
special treatment sections will be run by a warden in an enclosed
cubicle with a view of the yards and ablution centers. There will
also be an enclosed central command center that can override
everything else, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Prisoners in a SPM will spend 23 hours a day alone and then
one hour in cages in open yards where they can talk to other
inmates.
</P>
<P>
Convicts taken to the special sections of the SPMs will be
alone for 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
Wessmann said over the next few years every province would
have either a CMAX section of a complete super maximum security
prison.
</P>
<P>
"Since the CMAX opened in Pretoria, incidents in prisons
around the country have already dropped considerably," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, there were also criticisms of the CMAX, saying that
it is "inhuman." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970928.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq to Receive 7 Groups of Iranian Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has agreed to receive
seven groups of overseas Iranians despite Iran's doubt over
Baghdad's intention of doing so.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi newspaper Al-Thawara today quoted Mowaffaq El-Nasseri,
board chairman of the Huda Company for Religious Tourism as saying
the applications of these Iranians to visit Muslim holy sites in
Iraq have been approved.
</P>
<P>
The groups of Iranian visitors reside in the Gulf region and
the U.S., El-Nasseri said, but he failed to mention the number of
the Iranian visitors and the dates of their arrival.
</P>
<P>
He said that his company keeps in contact with many travel and
tourist agencies in the United Arab Emirates, India, Thailand,
Tanzania, Jordan and some southeast Asian countries with the aim
of making arrangements for Iranians residing in those countries to
come to visit Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and Iran fought an eight-year war from 1980-88 and are
still at odds with each other.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government has recently decided to allow Iranian
expatriates to visit Shiite Muslim holy shrines in Iraq as a
gesture for mending ties with Iran.
</P>
<P>
But Iran dismissed the offer, saying it was ambiguous and aimed
at diverting attention from unresolved issues between the two
countries, such as prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
Shiites and Sunnis are the two major factions of Islam. Iran is
the only Shiite-dominated country in the region but the most
important Shiite shrines are in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
