Australian from taking his 11th straight race by just 0.069 on the
hot and dusty Sentul track.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese went into the lead on the eighth lap of the 30-lap
race. Doohan managed to reclaim the lead but could never shake off
Okada.
</P>
<P>
The Australian star, who has already sealed his fourth world
title this year, has now won 12 races in 1997 and come second
twice.
</P>
<P>
Okada clocked 43 minutes 22.010 seconds over the 30 laps.
</P>
<P>
Spaniard Alex Criville, also on a Honda, was third after
plunging into a safety sand pit and brilliantly managing to keep
his machine going to get back on the track.  
