<HEADLINE> PNA: Washington Talks Last Chance to Save Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 28 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official
said today that a U.S.-brokered Palestinian-Israeli talks in
Washington might be the last chance to revive the stumbling peace
drive, Egypt's Middle East News Agency (MENA) reported.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with MENA, Fasail Husseini, minister in charge
of Jerusalem Affairs at the Palestinian National Authority (PNA),
expressed hope that U.S. proposals presented in the past few days
would help revive Palestinian-Israeli negotiations.
</P>
<P>
However, the hope for a breakthrough at the suggested
Palestinian-Israeli talks is widely considered as almost
impossible in view of the severe situation for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Adding to the tension brought about by the peace stalemate
since last March, Israel has announced plans to construct 300 new
housing units in the West Bank town of Efrat, and its troops have
trained for a possible all-out war with Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"Israel's plans to expand its settlements at this particular
time could be attributed to its desire to blow up the U.S. efforts
aiming at salvaging the deadlocked peacemaking," he said.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who strongly advocated the Washington talks during
her maiden trip to the region early this month, on Friday
criticized the Israeli plan as "an unnecessary kind of a step when
what we are trying to do is to create the best climate" for peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials have held separate talks with Palestinian and
Israeli peace teams ahead of the key meeting between Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy and Palestinian negotiator Mahmoud
Abbas in New York tomorrow that will be hosted by Albright.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
