<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatari Economy Reeling Under Heavy Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Qatari economy is reeling
under a burden of nearly 6 billion U.S. dollars of debt, one of
the heaviest in the world, local newspaper Khaleej Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The debt built up to finance projects aimed at transforming
Qatar into the world's biggest liquefied natural gas (LNG)
producer accounts for 79 percent of the country's gross domestic
product (GDP), the paper quoted an official report of the Arab
League-affiliated Inter-Arab Investment Guarantee Corporation as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Qatar's debt servicing accounts for 20 percent of the GDP and
45 percent of exports, one of the highest in the world, according
to the report of the economies of the Arab League's 22 members.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf state, a member of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC), owes 5.7 billion dollars to
international banks and other creditors and the debt is set to
increase as more funds are borrowed for LNG ventures, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
"The debt is expected to rise in the coming years because of
the ambitious investment plans and their financing needs,
especially concerning projects to develop the North Field," the
report said.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the subsequent increase in debt servicing, the
situation will begin to improve at the start of the next century
when those projects begin yielding high investment returns," the
report added.
</P>
<P>
Qatar's North Field is by far the largest known gas basin in
the world, containing nearly 10 trillion cubic meters of
non-associated gas, accounting for around 7 percent of the global
gas reserves.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the investment to develop the field could
reach 15 billion dollars and the production could hit 30 million
tonnes in 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
