<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Immigrants Plaguing Southern Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The decline in war refugees
in southern Africa due to reduced military conflicts has shifted
focus on the plight of immigrants being accused of destabilizing
and straining the region's economies, Sunday Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
Known as "economic refugees", migrants have become the latest
thorn in the flesh for a region striving to recover from decades
of liberation and civil wars that shattered its economies, the
Zimbabwe weekly says.
</P>
<P>
Immigrants, despite their contributions to host countries'
economies, are viewed with hostility.
</P>
<P>
Though they are found in every country, South Africa has
become the most attractive haven and it has crudely intensified
its crackdown to flush them out, only for them to return through
the back door.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that between 2.5 million and 4.1 million
illegal immigrants live in South Africa, the bulk of them from
Mozambique, Lesotho and Zimbabwe. Malawi, Zambia, Botswana and
Swaziland also contribute significant numbers.
</P>
<P>
South Africa accuses the immigrants of distorting economic
performance, threatening its border security, drug and arms
smuggling and all sorts of crimes.
</P>
<P>
The paper reported the migrants were recently a focus of
discussion during the 10th anniversary colloquium of the southern
Africa political economic series which concluded that labor
migration is a permanent phenomenon that cannot be swished away
unless economic disparities within the region are corrected.
</P>
<P>
South African Labor Minister Tito Mboweni held the migrant
inflow would continue as long as his country's income levels were
better than in the rest of the region.
</P>
<P>
He called on other countries to increase real earnings to
retain skills and maintain production levels that create
employment.
</P>
<P>
"If this is done, countries will stop resenting labor migration
and so efficient allocation of labor must be promoted," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
