<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiluba Urges Investors to Stay in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba has appealed to foreign investors not to leave his
country because the economy is on the way to recovery.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to government officials Saturday at Freedom Park in
Kitwe, 300 kilometers north of the capital, Chiluba said while
foreign investors work under difficult circumstances, they should
continue to stay, Sunday Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
Zambia is an ideal investment location and foreign investors
can make good returns for their money, said the president.
</P>
<P>
These remarks are made undoubtedly to counter several big
investors's claimed withdrawal from Zambia following last month's
closure of Dunlop Tyres Company Limited, the only foreign funded
tyre manufacturing company in the country.
</P>
<P>
Dunlop's closure was attributed to the importation of heavily
subsidized tyres imported from South Africa and the government's
failure to protect the country's fragile manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Chiluba has accused some trade partners in
the region intend to turn Zambia into a "dumping ground" through
"unfair competition".
</P>
<P>
During Saturday's speech, Chiluba stressed that although there
have been difficult circumstances, Zambia is both a member of the
Southern African Development Community and the Common Markets for
Eastern and Southern African and it is the one of the two
countries in the region which has no exchange controls, according
to the paper.
</P>
<P>
However, he cautioned those who wish to invest in the country
to have long-term plans instead of just making money and going
back to their home countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
