<HEADLINE> UAE Oil Reserves Put at 100 Billion Barrels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The proven oil reserves for
the United Arab Emirates (UAE) now stand at around 100 billion
barrels, tripling those in the 1970s, according to the country's
oil minister.
</P>
<P>
Obeid bin Saif al Nasir was quoted in the latest issue of the
Emirates Today monthly as saying that the natural gas reserves are
at 6 trillion cubic meters, nearly ten times of those in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
These developments, which made the UAE one of the world's
leading oil-rich countries, were due to continuous efforts in
developing the resources, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that his country, a member of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (Opec), will continue to adhere to
its Opec-assigned quota and "not to ask for an increase until Opec
increased its ceiling."
</P>
<P>
The UAE's quota is 2.161 million barrels per day. And the oil
industry takes up about 35 percent share in the financial income
for the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
