<HEADLINE> Israel Trade Unions Holds Nationwide General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 28 (Xinhua)-- The Israeli Federation of
Trade Unions (Histadrut) today organized a nationwide general
strike against the government's economic and pension policies.
</P>
<P>
The strike, began at 6:00 am (local time), will last till
14:00 pm as ordered by the Israeli National Labor Court, which
tried its best Saturday night, but failed to help the government
and Histadrut make compromise over their disputes.
</P>
<P>
The Histadrut said that a total of about half a million of
workers and staff from both public and private sectors
participate in the general strike, the largest in Israel's
history.
</P>
<P>
The strike paralyzed all government offices, including the
national insurance institutes, the employment service, local
authorities, public schools, banks and postal offices as well as
railway and bus lines.
</P>
<P>
The national health services, such as hospitals and clinics,
only operate on emergency cases.
</P>
<P>
The Histadrut is angry with new government budget cuts to
pension funds and a general restructuring of Israel's economy,
which involves privatization of state-owned corporations.
</P>
<P>
It requested the government to honor the existing agreement
signed in 1995 by the then leaders of the government and trade
unions, but the current government refused to recognize the
agreement, saying that it is nonbinding.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry and the Histadrut could not reach a
compromise Saturday night over this issue even with the help of
the Labor Court. The Histadrut then ordered today's strike.
</P>
<P>
The plans of today's strike also brought chaos Saturday night
to Ben-Gurion Airport. El Al, the Israeli Airlines, had to
rechedule 25 flights to transport about 3,500 passengers out
from the airport. The airport staff also joined today's strike,
and the airport closed down to air traffic.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that representatives of both the government
and Histadrut would meet again this afternoon or evening to
negotiate over the pension issue. The Histadrut said that the
strike will continue if the government does not give in.
</P>
</TEXT>
