<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel: Iran's Missile Program Threatens Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai has said that Iran is nearly completing its
development of long-range missiles that will threaten both Israeli
and U.S. security.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published by the Jerusalem Post daily today,
Mordechai said "Iran is on the verge of achieving the capability
of producing long-range missiles that have strategic dangers to
Israel, as well as to U.S. interests in the region."
</P>
<P>
Israel and the United States believe, on the basis of latest
intelligence information, that Iran's medium-ranged ballistic
missile and nuclear weapons programs have progressed faster than
expected, Mordechai said.
</P>
<P>
The most impressive progress was made in Iran's missile
development program with the aid of Russia, he added.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister claimed that at the current pace of
development, Tehran would have missiles that can reach Israel,
Gulf states, Asia and parts of Europe by 1999. He believed that
Iran also wants to increase its chemical weapons and produce
biological and nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted western intelligence officials as saying
that Iran has embarked on three missile programs. One has a range
of 1,500 kilomaters, which covers Israel, Gulf states and Asia;
another has a range of 3,000 kilometers, which can hit much of
Western Europe; and the third has a range of 5,500 kilometers that
is to be largely aimed at striking the U.S. targets in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said that the U.S. intelligence officials have a
more alarming assessment than their Israeli colleagues of how
close Iran is to achieving its goal. He added that the new
intelligence showed that Russia had violated months of pledges
to stop aid to Iran's missile and non-conventional weapons
programs.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel and the U.S. disagreed over how to pressure
Russia to immediately stop assisting Iran's missile programs. The
U.S. government wants to concentrate on quiet diplomatic efforts,
while Israel is lobbying the U.S. Congress to cut off U.S. aid to
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
But he acknowledged that the U.S. government has so far
refused to use the cutoff of U.S. economic aid to Russia as a
lever to stop Russian aid to Iran's missile programs. Russia
received 95 million dollars in aid from the U.S. in 1997, and the
U.S. government is asking the Congress for 225 million dollars
for Russia in 1998.
</P>
<P>
For its part, Russia has strongly denied that it is helping
Iran develop ballistic missile programs, saying its nuclear aid to
Iran is limited to developing a civilian nuclear reactor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970928.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials Bribed for Illegal Immigration into S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Officials in South
Africa's Home Affairs Ministry were paid 710,000 U.S. Dollars in
bribes to grant 54 Taiwanese families permanent residence, a
local weekly City Press revealed today.
</P>
<P>
According to the weekly's investigation report, the ministry
has confirmed that the families, consisting of 272 people, were
granted permanent residence after arriving in South Africa in
1995 on tourist visas.
</P>
<P>
The aliens control act prohibits foreigners who arrive in
South Africa as tourists from working in the country.
</P>
<P>
This means the corrupt officials were paid almost 14,200
dollars per family, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
It is not yet known if this is just the tip of the iceberg, as
more than 10,000 people have been granted permanent residence by
the ministry during the past two years, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's spokesman, Hennie Meyer, told the weekly that a
department official and a former employee involved in the scandal
are being investigated by the police.
</P>
<P>
An attorney for the families has applied for permission for
the illegal Taiwanese immigrants to remain in the country, saying
the families incurred enormous costs to settle here through an
immigration agent who allegedly dealt with the corrupt officials.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that the immigrants have invested millions of Rands
in properties and businesses and should they be forced to leave
both these people and South Africa would suffer financial loss.
</P>
<P>
But the parliament standing committee of the ruling African
National Congress wants the ministry to deport the families back
to Taiwan, saying they can follow proper procedures if they are
interested in settling in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Visitors on tourist visas are not permitted to apply for
permanent residence while in the country. Applications for
permanent residence must be made from the applicant's home
country and more than 2,000 U.S. Dollars must be deposited with
the Ministry of Home Affairs if the permanent residence is
granted.
</P>
<P>
Desmond Lockey, the standing committee's chairman, said the
families "have broken the country's laws by bribing officials to
gain permanent residence status."
</P>
<P>
"No country in the world would allow such a practice and we
must not be called on to change our rules for certain people," he
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
