<DOCNO> XIE19970928.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ACP Countries Worried About Expiry of Lome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Uncertainty and fear have set
in among ACP states over the pending expiry in year 2000 of the
Lome Convention and its trade packages which have over the years
facilitated preferential access to European markets.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Mail reported today that Lome Conventions have
since 1975 provided frameworks for trade, development and aid
between the European Union and the 70-member African, Caribbean
and Pacific (ACP) grouping of former European colonies.
</P>
<P>
But the establishment of the World Trade Organization (WTO),
two years ago, threatens to pull the carpet from under the ACP
feet if it fails to negotiate for the extension of Lome
Convention beyond the year 2000 or retain preferential terms.
</P>
<P>
The WTO seeks to open trade to all world economies and reduce
or even remove aid packages and preferential agreements.
</P>
<P>
"All this is a threat to Africa and calls for urgency on our
part. If we do not fight in real terms then we are down," said
economist of Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions Godfrey Kanyenze.
</P>
<P>
For fear of weakening their cause through individual country
negotiations, the ACP, led by Zimbabwe current chairman of
chambers of commerce, has formed a strong bloc which is to meet
in Gabon in November to define its common position before a
meeting in Brussels, Belgium, in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
Among the ACP demands is the relaxation of restrictive trade
regulations and stringent lending, borrowing and aid packages.
Already, the 14-member southern African development community
prefers Lome Convention to continue for 10 years after the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted experts saying that current developments
reflect a rapid transformation of world economies which has gone
through in the past 22 years.
</P>
<P>
Experts held that the 1989 fall of the Soviet Union economy,
changes in eastern Europe and forced structural adjustment
programs in developing countries have shaken the foundations of
the convention.
</P>
<P>
Europe is now looking at expanding eastwards and strengthening
ties there while further marginalizing Africa.
</P>
<P>
To compound its woes, an EU's "green paper" published recently
concludes that aid to ACP countries through the European
Development Fund has not yielded expected results in the economic
growth of these countries.
</P>
<P>
It suggests that all aid given to Africa be converted to
trade, the paper reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970928.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPPCC Vice-Chairwoman Meets US Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- He Luli, vice-chairwoman of
the National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC), met here today with a delegation
from the Pennsylvania Peace Links of the United States led by its
president Anne Kuhn.
</P>
<P>
He, also president of the Chinese People's Association for
Peace and Disarmament, briefed the US visitors on China's domestic
situation as well as its reform and opening-up.
</P>
<P>
Kuhn said that the Pennsylvania Peace Links will work together
with the Chinese People's Association for Peace and Disarmament to
maintain world peace and enhance friendship between the people of
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
