<DOCNO> XIE19970928.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why Least Developed States Fail to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Agricultural output of
the 48 Least Developed Countries (LDCs) in 1990-1994 had an
annual average growth rate of two percent, one pc less than their
annual average population growth rate, a U.N. report said.
</P>
<P>
The UN Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) said in
its "the least developed countries 1997 report" that food imports
and food aid have been significant in meeting the shortfall
between domestic agricultural production and food requirements in
many LDCs.
</P>
<P>
In 1990-1993, LDCs food imports averaged 3.6 percent of gross
domestic product (GDP), while African LDCs imports reached almost
5 percent over the same period, and these African LDCs form the
bulk of the LDC group.
</P>
<P>
It is noteworthy that agriculture is the most important
economic activity in LDCs. In the early 1990s this sector
provided about a third of the GDP of all LDCs, and employed more
than two-thirds of the labor force.
</P>
<P>
Why then, 20 years after the "green revolution", have many
LDCs failed to improve their agricultural productivity?
</P>
<P>
Experts from the UNCTAD believed that the sluggish growth in
per capita agricultural production in LDCs can be explained by
various factors.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, the agricultural and food production in most of LDCs
are dependent upon weather. The traditional production relations,
rudimentary technology and simple hand-held tools hinder farming
development.
</P>
<P>
Even where yield-enhancing technologies are available in
developing countries, farmers in many of LDCs have increased
their output simply by extending into virgin lands. They have not
adopted, on a wide scale, yield-enhancing agricultural
technologies, such as high-yielding varieties and irrigation.
</P>
<P>
For example, as a big agricultural production country in
Africa, Ethiopia has only 160,000 hectares of land under
irrigation out of the 3.5 million hectares of potentially
irrigable area.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, most LDC governments often neglected and made
inadequate investment into the agricultural sector. development
of agriculture in LDCs.
</P>
<P>
They have not adequately financed such physical and social
infrastructure as roads, water facilities, education and health
in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Rural roads in LDCs are mostly dirt tracks, which are
impassable during the rainy season. And uneducated farmers may
not be as receptive to new ideals and technology as educated one.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, past macro-economic policies in most LDC governments
have failed to courage the agricultural production. For example,
the control of, or the intervention in, input supply,
agricultural processing and marketing, in the case of food crops
to ensure cheap food for urban dwellers, have created many
distortions in agricultural trade.
</P>
<P>
Administered prices, for various crops whose marketing are
controlled by the government, are often insufficient to cover
total costs of production, thus further distorting the market.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, agricultural exports are discouraged by heavy
explicite taxation and overvalued domestic currencies.
</P>
<P>
Rubens Ricupero, Secretary General of UNCTAD pointed out that
"a strong and well developed agricultural sector is a means to
broader developmental ends."
</P>
<P>
By increasing rural incomes, it will also lead to an expansion
of domestic markets. A robust agricultural policy is also a key
to an integrated poverty alleviation strategy, given that the
poorest people in LDCs tend to live in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Now UNCTAD calls on LDC governments to prioritize their often
neglected agricultural sector if they want to attain, and then
sustain, high growth rates.
</P>
<P>
The experts from UNCTAD believe that to achieve this goal, the
advise and support should be offered to governments as regards
giving higher priority to sound national agricultural policies
and their adjustment to new international trade regimes.
</P>
<P>
Effort should also be made in revitalizing national
agricultural extension, training and research facilities with
particular emphasis on creating capabilities for reaching
resource-poor and female farmers.
</P>
<P>
Stress should be put on the re-orientation of national
extension and research systems with the aim of creating more
environmentally sustainable agricultural systems.
</P>
<P>
Finally, the LDCs should have close cooperation with the
international agricultural research systems to ensure a clear
focus on production impacts on farmers' fields in international
research efforts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970928.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 40 Percent of Bangladesh's Mangroves "Sick" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The world's greatest mangrove
forest, situated in the Bangladesh's southwest district of Khulna,
is "sick" and scientists suspect that global warming is the cause.
</P>
<P>
Already 40 percent of the 5,800 square kilometer forest
fringing the Bay of Bengal is affected by "top-dying" disease
which kills off the mangroves from the top down, the newspaper New
Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
Now, in an attempt to stop the disease, scientists have begun a
three-year project funded by the British government's Overseas
Development Administration to monitor the forest, the newspaper
added.
</P>
<P>
If the scientists' suspicions are found to be true and nothing
is done to protect the forest in Sundarbans, the effects would be
both devastating and far-reaching, the newspaper continued.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh would be left to face a decimated fishing industry,
increased flooding and the loss of endangered animals, including
the world's largest concentration of royal Bengal tigers, the
newspaper quoted project director Terry Thomas as warning.
</P>
<P>
The wildlife would be badly hit in Bangladesh with about 500
types of birds and 40 species of animal, including the globally
endangered salt water crocodile, living in the forest, the
newspaper stated, adding Bangladesh would also lose its only
substantial timber resource.
</P>
<P>
"The disappearance of Sundarbans mangroves, which is the only
thing stopping Bangladesh from sliding into the Bay of Bengal,
would be an ecological catastrophe," said Keith Burd, director of
the British Council in Bangladesh which is administering the
project.
</P>
<P>
The "sick" mangroves in Sundarbans indicate that already global
warming may be having an impact on sea levels in the Bay of
Bengal, according to Thomas.
</P>
<P>
The fresh water channels are becoming increasingly saline, and
although no one knows yet for sure, "we think this may be behind
the top dying," Thomas said, adding that it also possibly
indicates a rise in sea levels which would push salt water back up
into the channels.
</P>
<P>
The initial phase of the project, which has got under way last
April, will lay a foundation for fighting back against the
catastrophe, the newspaper stated.
</P>
<P>
The ultimate aim of the project is to establish Khulna, located
80 kilometers to the north of the mangroves, as a regional center
to offer graduated specific training in the ecology and
sustainable management of tropical coastal zones, the newspaper
added.
</P>
<P>
Losing the forest would be devastating for the fisheries and
therefore the economies of Bangladesh, Thailand, Myanmar and
India, according to a lecturer in forestry at Khulna University.
</P>
<P>
The governments of India, Malaysia, Indonesia, the Philippines,
Papua New Guinea and Australia are keeping a close eye on the
Sundarbans situation, because their own mangrove forests will also
suffer similar decimation if global warming is conclusively found
to lie behind mangrove sickness, the newspaper noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970928.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
