<HEADLINE> Kenyan Lobby Group Calls off Strike Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The National Convention
Executive Council (NCEC) has decided to cancel a plan of strike
scheduled on October 8 and 9, The Sunday Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly paper quoted NCEC spokesman Kivutha Kibwana as
saying Saturday that the cancellation action was aimed at giving
a chance to the expected consultations with other stake-holders
of the on-going debate on the two amended bills in Kenya's
parliament.
</P>
<P>
"We demand that the government works out a modality to hold
dialogue with NCEC" on the content of the current reforms based
on the reforms package put forward by the Inter-Parties
Parliamentary Group (IPPG), he noted.
</P>
<P>
The NCEC which is the lobby group of the opposition parties in
Kenya has always dismissed the IPPG minimum constitutional,
administrative and legal reforms package as inadequate for
facilitating free and fair elections.
</P>
<P>
Kibwana said that the NCEC would review the propriety of
reviving mass action after Kenya's parliament had concluded its
debate on the minimum reform agenda.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, he noted that the NCEC would organize
provincial public rallies and meet-the-people tours to discuss
the IPPG proposals with the Kenyan people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
