<HEADLINE> Floods Inflict Heavy Losses on Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's economy has
suffered an estimated loss of about 40 billion rupees (about 1
billion U.S. dollars) because of floods since 1988, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Another 40 billion rupees has been spent on the import of food,
owing to a lack of reservoirs to hold the water and use it to
irrigate farmland, said the officials with the Pakistan
Engineering Congress.
</P>
<P>
"It is unfortunate that we are not deriving maximum benefits
from the sweet river water, which during floods, have been flowing
into the sea un-utilized," they said.
</P>
<P>
If flood water is not contained in storage schemes and used to
augment food supplies, Pakistan would face a severe famine as the
country enters the next century, the officials warned.
</P>
<P>
The government should take immediate measures including
constructing more major reservoirs to harness the flood water,
they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
