<HEADLINE> Rational Use of Drugs Urged in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Chief Medical Officer
in Tanzania's Ministry of Health Gabriel Upunda has called for
rational use of drugs to ease financial burden.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal while opening an international course on
the promotion of rational drug use in Dar es Salaam at the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Upunda noted that developing countries can save their meager
resources used in importing expensive drugs if the medicines are
rationally used.
</P>
<P>
He said many developing countries at present have tight
budgets and they are forced to adopt and implement new health
financing strategies with which parents, using health care
facilities, are being asked to share the cost of medicines and
other services.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from personnel emoluments, the great part of the health
budget is spent on drugs," Upunda said.
</P>
<P>
"Most of these drugs are imported, thus exhausting the meager
foreign exchange earnings of the least developed countries such
as Tanzania," Upunda said, stressing when drugs are used
rationally there is a bigger chance that the drugs can be made
available at health centers.
</P>
<P>
Over 30 people from 12 countries are taking part in the
course. 
</P>
</TEXT>
