<HEADLINE> By-laws Against Genital Mutilations Enhanced in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Serengeti District
Council of Mara Region in northern Tanzania has formulated
by-laws which will make female circumcision an offense.
</P>
<P>
The by-laws were made and approved by councillors and have
been sent to the prime minister for approval before they become
effective, according to a news dispatch from Serengeti quoting
district commissioner Laban Makunenge as saying on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
If the by-laws sail through, parents who circumcise their
daughters will face traditional fines and other punitive
measures, said the district commissioner.
</P>
<P>
Serengeti is the second district in Mara Region after Tarime
where female circumcision is rampant with all the major tribes
there practising female circumcision. Women who are not
circumcised are regarded incomplete and cannot get married.
</P>
<P>
Genital mutilation causes sufferings to women and resulted in
high rate of mortality in areas where such habits are practised.
</P>
<P>
Female circumcision-related deaths in Tarime District are
high, with 20 to 25 out of 5,000 circumcised girls dying annually
of complications particularly because of bleeding and infections,
according to Peter Mwera, president of the Save Children of
Tarime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
