<HEADLINE> Haze Drives More Singaporeans Abroad for Fresh Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The haze disaster, which is
turning for the worse in the region, has not only stopped overseas
tourists from coming to Singapore, but also has driven more
Singaporeans abroad for fresh air, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper Sunday Times said today that figures from local
travel agents showed that there has been a growing number of
people leaving lately, resulting in increases in tour bookings in
the months of September and October, which is unusual because this
is an off-peak season.
</P>
<P>
At one travel agency, bookings went up by almost a third. More
than 250 people are leaving each week while there were fewer than
200 a week this time last year.
</P>
<P>
Another travel agency saw its bookings for Australia tours
going up by 60 percent while a third one got inquiries over the
phone for all tour packages at about 70 per hour.
</P>
<P>
The most popular destination, said the travel agents, is
Australia, followed by the United States and European countries.
</P>
<P>
Most Singaporeans prefer Australia because it is far enough to
avoid the haze but close enough to be affordable, the report said.
</P>
