surge that battered several Bangladesh coastal districts early
Saturday morning left 36 people dead, according to information
reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The cyclone, which blew at a speed of 150 kilometers per hour
and was accompanied with five-feet-high (about 1.5 meters) tidal
surge, also left unspecified number of people injured and damaged
thousands of houses and more than 5,000 acres (about 2,000
hectares) of standing crops.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 to 30 percent of standing crops in the cyclone-hit
areas were damaged while 2,500 families were affected and more
than 1,000 houses collapsed.
</P>
<P>
The number of casualties was low mainly because of early
effective warnings, forced evacuation and efforts made by
thousands of volunteers from the Red Crescent Society.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina has asked the concerned
authorities, including the Armed Forces, to remain alert and
continue the rescue work in areas hit by the cyclonic storm.
</P>
<P>
She directed the district administrations to ascertain the
actual casualty figures and damage caused by the cyclone.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also asked the officials to conduct relief
operations on a priority basis after identifying the worst-hit
areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
