<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Confirms Loss of Colombo-Bound Mortars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 28 (Xinhua) -- After a silence of nearly
three months, official confirmation has finally been given that a
consignment of 32,400 mortar bombs ordered from Zimbabwe by the
Sri Lankan Army, has gone missing.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports said today that the missing bombs had
fallen into the hands of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
(LTTE).
</P>
<P>
An independent Zimbabwean newspaper, the Financial Gazette, on
Thursday quoted Tshinga Dube, head of the government-owned
Zimbabwe Defense Industries (ZDI) as saying the 81-mm mortar
rounds had disappeared at sea after the cargo vessel carrying them
left for Colombo on July 2, the local press said.
</P>
<P>
Dube was quoted as saying the International Police Organization
(Interpol) was still trying to trace the whereabouts of the
missing ship and its captain.
</P>
<P>
The ship, Stillus Limmassul, was loaded with the mortar bombs
at the Mozambican port of Beira. It last docked at a port in
Madagascar en route to Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan troops operating in the north and east of the
country reported unusually heavy mortar shelling from the rebels
in the past month, which they believed indicated that the Tamil
rebels had got the shipment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an Israeli arms dealer, Ben Tsoi, was also involved
in the missing of the consignment. The ZDI claimed to have
contracted with Tsoi to arrange the transportation of the bombs.
</P>
<P>
However, Tsoi has flatly denied that he had handled the
transportation. The Israeli national was also hunted by the
Interpol for investigations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
