<HEADLINE> Share Prices on BSE Stage Smart Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The downward march on the
Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) last week was halted and the share
prices staged a smart recovery in the wake of hectic short
covering and purchases by domestic institutions and foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
Although the weak trend continued even in the opening session
of the new account, speculatives later met with good support as
operators rushed to cover their short positions.
</P>
<P>
And together with buying by financial institutions and
increasing purchases by foreign funds in the light of the
appreciating Indian rupee against the U.S. dollar without any
intervention by the Reserve Bank of India, the sensitive index was
pushed up by more than 100 points.
</P>
<P>
The index, which dipped by 54.13 points to 3770.99 on Monday,
later recovered to close the week at 3925.24 as against last
weekend's close of 3825.12, showing a rise of 100.12 points.
</P>
<P>
The national index rose by 39.58 points to end the week at
1703.63 from the previous weekend's close of 1664.05. The BSE-200
and the U.S. dollar index were quoted substantially up at the
weekend at 380.01 and 174.67 compared with last weekend's closes
of 373.44 and 170.81.
</P>
<P>
Brokers expected a further improvement in the prices in the
initial stages next week, but they noted that it is difficult to
predict the behavior of the market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
