<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haze Over Southern Thailand Starts to Lessen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The haze caused by massive
Indonesian forest fires has started to lessen on the whole in
southern Thailand, but the problem still remains serious in some
provinces.
</P>
<P>
The air quality was improving in southern Thailand's Songkhla,
Phuket, Satun and Surat Thani provinces, the Thai Public Health
Ministry said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The dust particles were measured at 50 micrograms per cubic
meters on Saturday, down from the level of 60 micrograms measured
earlier, according to the ministry, which has established mobile
air-quality monitoring units there.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the improvement, the situation is still far
from perfect, officials from the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
In some parts of Satun Province, road visibility is only within
one kilometer while on the sea, it is only 300 meters, blocking
some small boats without navigating equipment from going offshore.
</P>
<P>
In Trang Province, the haze forced Thai Airways International
to cancel a domestic flight on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The choking smoke produced from Indonesian forest fires was
brought to southern Thailand through Malaysia by wind earlier this
week, covering most of southern Thailand with Trang Province hit
hardest.
</P>
<P>
The smoke has made people in southern Thailand suffer from
respiratory aliments, forced some airlines to cancel some flights
and blocked fishing boats from going offshore.  
</P>
</TEXT>
