<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Declares Smog Emergency in Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Mexico City declared a
phase one pollution emergency today and ordered cars off the roads
and factories working at partial capacity, the city government
said.
</P>
<P>
The Metropolitan Environment Commission made the decision this
afternoon as ozone levels went above allowable readings.
</P>
<P>
Under the emergency rules, half of the city's vehicles will be
pulled from the road, while factories are only allowed to work at
30-40 percent of capacity. One fifth of the gas stations will be
shut down and all outdoor sports activities will be called off in
schools.
</P>
<P>
The Metropolitan Indice of Air Quality (IMECA), which measures
ozone levels, reached 270 in the northeast part of the city, high
enough to trigger the alarm.
</P>
<P>
A reading of 250 on the IMECA scale is considered a hazardous
level. Readings above 100 is considered by international standards
to be dangerous to the health.
</P>
<P>
Ozone is a pollutant created when car fumes mix with solar
radiation. There are an estimated 3 million cars on the road in
the city.
</P>
<P>
Mexico City, high in a mountain basin, is one of the most
polluted in the world, where sun and smog produce a toxic brew
that often smothers the city.
</P>
<P>
This was the second time this year that the city declared a
state of environmental emergency. The incidence of respiratory and
cardiovascular diseases has risen markedly in recent days as a
result of the dense smog. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
