<HEADLINE> Costa Rica to Defend Banana Export Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, September 27 (Xinhua) -- A Costa Rican delegation led
by Foreign Trade Minister Jose Miguel Salazar will travel to
European countries in the next few days to defend the country's
quota rights of banana exports, Costa Rican government sources
said today.
</P>
<P>
Under the European Union (EU) banana import system, Costa Rica
can export 24 percent of the total Latin American banana
production to Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, the United States, Ecuador, Mexico and Guatemala never
accepted the quotas and granted discriminatory commercial
advantages to the former European colonies in Africa, Latin
America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
The World Trade Organization (WTO) considers that the quota
system violates international commerce rules and asked the EU to
change it.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica will suffer the negative consequences of the WTO
resolution, though the WTO's decision will not affect this year's
Costa Rican production.
</P>
<P>
"But we are not sitting on our haunches," said Salazar. For
this Costa Rica began contacting some of the countries to start a
dialogue on the matter, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
