<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Creates Committee on Desertification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Italy has set up a national
committee for fighting desertification on the eve of a
U.N. conference on the problem in Rome.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi signed an order to create
the committee today.
</P>
<P>
A quarter or 27 percent of the Italian territory is considered
as facing the risk of desertification, data released by the
government show.
</P>
<P>
Large areas of arable land in Italy have changed or are
changing into deserts after they were abandoned by rural
population who moved to settle in cities.
</P>
<P>
The problem is becoming more and more acute with increasing
industrialization.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. conference on global desertification starting on
September 30 will bring together representatives and experts from
countries which have signed the International Convention to Combat
Desertifiation.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. figures, desertification causes an annual
revenue loss of 42 million U.S. dollars worldwide and affects 250
million people all over the world and a billion more people are at
risk.
</P>
<P>
In North America, desertification engulfs 74 percent of the
land while 73 percent of the African continent is threatened. In
Europe, Italy and Spain need to address the problem more seriously
and the risk of desertification in Asia and South America is
increasing.
</P>
<P>
The 10-day U.N. conference aims to find ways to implements the
Desertification Convention adopted on December 29, 1996 and
already ratified by 108 countries.
</P>
<P>
The countries who signed the Convention pledge to work out a
long-term strategy to fight desertification based on international
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
